  "prompt": "What is a good substitute for chipotle powder?",
  "response": "If you don't have chipotle powder on hand, there are several substitutes that you can use to achieve a similar smoky and spicy flavor. Here are some alternatives:\n\n1. **Smoked Paprika**: This is a great substitute as it provides a smoky flavor similar to chipotle. You can use it in a 1:1 ratio.\n \n2. **Ancho Chili Powder**: This powder is made from dried poblano peppers and offers a mild heat with a slightly sweet and smoky flavor. It can be used as a substitute, though you might want to add a bit of cayenne pepper for more heat.\n\n3. **Cayenne Pepper**: For heat without the smokiness, cayenne pepper can be used. However, use it sparingly because it's significantly hotter than chipotle powder.\n\n4. **Adobo Sauce**: If you have canned chipotle peppers in adobo sauce, you can use the sauce as a substitute. It's both smoky and spicy.\n\n5. **Chili Powder**: A general chili powder mix can be used as a substitute if you're in a pinch, though it may lack the smoky element. You can try combining it with smoked paprika to get a closer flavor profile.\n\nRemember to adjust the quantities to taste, as some substitutes might be spicier than others.",
